Content: Select choices before TWO details from Passage 1 that show why Gawaine chooses to pursue the Graal.

:box:	 :MC-A: Then uprose Sir Gawaine, :MC-B: who was a faithful knight and true man to his king, :MC-C: though a proud one and a hasty. :MC-D: He was filled with sorrow for the ruin that threatened his fair land.
	 :MC-E: “Now I do here avow,” he said, :MC-F: “that to-morrow, without fail, I shall set forth, :MC-G: and I shall labour with all the strength of my body and my soul :MC-H: to go in quest of the Holy Graal, :MC-I: so that if I be fit to see it and to bring it hither, :MC-J: this dear land may be saved from woe.”
	 :MC-K: So hot were his words :MC-L: that many of the better knights rose also, :MC-M: and raising their right hands did make a like avowal; ... (paragraphs 9 - 11)

Key.Rationale: This sentence reveals Gawaine's motivation: he wants to find the grail in order to bring peace to his kingdom.
This sentence reveals Gawaine's desire to find the grail in order to save his kingdom.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
In Passage 2, what theme is suggested by Graham's situation?

A.Choice: First instincts are usually correct.

B.Choice: A sense of adventure can solve many problems.

C.Choice: Planning ahead can help one understand a situation more clearly.

D.Choice: People will do whatever is necessary to keep what is important to them.

Key.Rationale: The man agrees to the risky proposition to search for buried treasure since it seems to be the only way for him to keep his family's property.

Content: Which quotation helps develop the theme in Part A?

A.Choice: “'Luckily for me — for the both of us, looks like — the real fortune is right here, beneath our feet.'” (paragraph 19)

B.Choice: “Graham's father had never mentioned having a brother; this man's story was preposterous.” (paragraph 20)

C.Choice: “'Either way, somewhere out there,' the man gestured grandly towards the farm outside the window, 'is a treasure.'” (paragraph 23)

D.Choice: “Graham turned to the old man and asked, 'How are we going to find it?'” (paragraph 25)

Key.Rationale: This quotation shows that Graham is considering the man's proposition to look for buried treasure in the hopes of keeping his family's property.

Content: Read the excerpt from Passage 1.

:box:	“Sir, I bring here a young knight, the which is of king's lineage, whereby the marvels of this court shall be accomplished, and the trial of this thy kingdom shall be brought to a happy end, if that may be. And the name of him is Galahad.” (paragraph 3)
What does the use of the word “trial” suggest in this excerpt?

A.Choice: The kingdom is under pressure from enemy countries.

B.Choice: The kingdom has endured many hardships in the past.

Key.Rationale: In this context, “trial” suggests situations that have oppressed the country, which the quest for the Graal seeks to put to an end.

C.Choice: The old man will judge those who fail to obtain the Graal.

D.Choice: The knights have a legal responsibility to pursue the Graal.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
How is the structure of Passage 2 different from the structure of Passage 1?

A.Choice: Passage 2 ends by foreshadowing what will happen next.

B.Choice: Passage 2 builds toward a climax as the story progresses.

C.Choice: Passage 2 describes the characters' thoughts and actions in between dialogue.

D.Choice: Passage 2 introduces the main character's conflict before anything else occurs.

Key.Rationale: Passage 2 begins by setting up the context for Graham's motivation to find the treasure, while in Passage 1 the reader learns of the king's motivations as the story progresses.

Content: Which aspect of the passages is affected by this difference in structure?

A.Choice: how the reader imagines the stories will end

B.Choice: the way the characters' goals are revealed

Key.Rationale: The different structures set up the characters' goals differently to the reader. In Passage 1, the reader finds out midway what the conflict is that affects how Sir Gawaine's goals are revealed. In Passage 2, the reader finds out immediately that Graham is about to lose his farm and finds out immediately how determined he is to keep it.

C.Choice: the number of ways the stories can be understood

D.Choice: how the reader knows what the main characters are thinking

Content: Read this excerpt from Passage 1.

:box:	“Sir,” said the king, “if it may be that ye know, will ye tell us what my knights must do to achieve the Holy Vessel, and thus bring peace into my kingdom in place of war? For many of those that are kings and barons under me are warring with each other, and threaten to rend this island of Britain, ... And it goeth to my heart to know this, and I have much dread.”
	“Sir king,” said the old white man, “none may tell you what shall be the end of this quest of the Holy Graal, ... ye war with each other, and are evil livers and full of pride and mastery, and if ye do not repent and stay your dishonour, then shall the Holy Vessel pass from Britain, and ruin and death and civil war shall stalk through the land and leave it desolate.”
How does the speaker's point of view in this excerpt increase the tension of Passage 1?

A.Choice: by showing that the power of the Graal has the potential to do harm

B.Choice: by showing that the Graal has likely been lost to the kingdom forever

C.Choice: by showing that Britain is less powerful than the knights believe it to be

D.Choice: by showing that the knights share responsibility for the condition of Britain

Key.Rationale: The speaker's use of the pronoun “ye,” and his direct address to the knights, indicate that he is accusing them of playing a role in the degradation of the country.

Content: Select TWO ways that the story in Passage 2 is similar to the story in Passage 1.

A.Choice: Both stories feature characters who share a common goal.

Key.Rationale: Both passages are set around a quest for an item.

B.Choice: Both stories include dialogue between characters with conflicting views.

C.Choice: Both stories feature central characters who change their point of view in the end.

D.Choice: Both stories describe the details of the setting to create a mysterious atmosphere.

E.Choice: Both stories present a challenge and a way for the central character to overcome it.

Key.Rationale: In Passage 2, Graham wants to secure the finances of his family farm, and in Passage 1, the king wants to resolve fighting in his kingdom.

Content: Select choices before TWO sentences from paragraph 1 of Passage 2 that suggest it would be easy for consumers to start using CFLs.

:box:	 :MC-A: CFLs are a type of fluorescent lamp. :MC-B: Many models of CFLs are available that are designed to replace traditional incandescent bulbs. :MC-C: The compact size of these CFLs allows them to fit into many existing incandescent light fixtures, including table and floor lamps commonly found in households. :MC-D: CFLs are very energy efficient, using approximately one quarter of the energy compared to traditional incandescent bulbs. :MC-E: CFLs also have a very long lifespan, typically 6000–15,000 hours compared to the 750–1,000 hours for a normal incandescent bulb. (paragraph 1)

Key.Rationale: This sentence supports the idea that CFLs are easy to start using because consumers will have the flexibility and freedom to choose from a variety of CFLs.
This sentence shows that CFLs are convenient to use because they can easily be used in existing incandescent light fixtures.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the central idea of Passage 2?

A.Choice: CFLs offer an inexpensive, more practical choice for consumers.

B.Choice: CFLs have many advantages over traditional light bulbs.

C.Choice: CFLs are a new, more efficient type of light bulb.

D.Choice: CFLs are very safe for people to use.

Key.Rationale: While presented as a general FAQ, the central idea of Passage 2 is that CFLs are generally believed to be safe to use.

Content: How is the central idea developed throughout Passage 2?

A.Choice: by comparing and contrasting CFLs with traditional bulbs

B.Choice: by detailing the way in which CFLs generate light

C.Choice: by responding to reported concerns about CFLs

Key.Rationale: The passage's Q&A format is used to respond to a series of concerns about CFL technology, thus promoting the idea that CFLs are safe to use.

D.Choice: by listing the various benefits of using CFLs

Content: How does the diagram in Passage 3 distinguish between the different types of light bulbs?

A.Choice: by showing the replacement costs associated with each type of light bulb

B.Choice: by showing the overall energy costs associated with each type of light bulb

Key.Rationale: The diagram in Passage 3 highlights the overall energy costs associated with each type of light bulb when all factors are taken into consideration (initial cost, lifetime, and efficiency).

C.Choice: by showing the amount of energy generated by each type of light bulb per hour of use

D.Choice: by showing the amount of waste generated by each type of light bulb when each is recycled

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the tone of paragraph 7 in Passage 2?

A.Choice: dismissive

B.Choice: reassuring

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 7 addresses concerns about the amount of mercury emitted by CFLs and gives a rare instance of when it would occur, contributing to a reassuring tone.

C.Choice: uplifting

D.Choice: fearful

Content: Fill in the bubble before the sentence from paragraph 7 that most clearly contributes to this tone.

:box:	 :MC-A: Like traditional tube-style fluorescent lamps, CFLs contain a small amount of mercury. :MC-B: It is the use of this small amount of mercury that allows any fluorescent lamp to produce visible illumination at much higher efficiency levels than incandescent lighting. :MC-C: Typical household CFLs contain less than 5 mg of mercury, which is a sphere about the size of the tip of a pen. :MC-D: CFLs do not emit mercury as they operate. :MC-E: The only way mercury could be emitted from a CFL would be if the outer glass tubing that contains the mercury were to break. (paragraph 7)

Key.Rationale: This detail demonstrates that mercury is emitted in CFLs only under rare circumstances when the outer tube is broken, which supports the reassuring tone in the paragraph.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Fill in the bubble before the sentence from paragraph 5 of Passage 2 that offers general safety advice about exposure to UV.

:box: :MC-A: The glass used in CFLs already provides a UV filtering effect. :MC-B: In addition, any additional glass, or plastic, or fabric used in lighting fixtures that is between you and the CFL will further reduce the already low levels to still lower levels since these materials act as additional UV filters. :MC-C: Increasing the distance between you and any radiation source, including CFLs, will also reduce the small level to a lower level. (paragraph 5)

Key.Rationale: This detail describes a practical step that can be taken in order to reduce exposure to UV.

Content: What key idea from Passage 2 does the sentence chosen in Part A support?

A.Choice: CFLs fail to adequately filter exposure to UV.

B.Choice: There are additional ways to lessen exposure to UV.

Key.Rationale: The sentence chosen in Part A describes one way that people can decrease their exposure to UV, supporting the key idea that there are many ways to do this.

C.Choice: CFLs expose people to less UV than other types of bulbs.

D.Choice: There are many lighting fixture that block exposure to UV.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the interviewer's purpose in Passage 1?

A.Choice: to find solutions to the dangers posed by CFLs

B.Choice: to explore the costs and benefits of using CFLs

C.Choice: to question consumers about their opinion of CFLs

D.Choice: to promote the use of CFLs over incandescent bulbs

Key.Rationale: While the interview format and the interviewer's questions give some appearance of impartiality, it is clear that the purpose of the podcast is to promote CFL use.

Content: How does the interviewer achieve her purpose in Passage 1?

A.Choice: by asking questions of people who support and people who oppose CFL use

B.Choice: by asking questions that emphasize advantages of and minimize concerns about CFLs

Key.Rationale: Just enough information is presented on a potential concern regarding CFL bulbs to allow the speakers to address the topic and then dismiss it as unimportant.

C.Choice: by limiting the questions to those addressing health and safety concerns related to CFLs

D.Choice: by limiting the questions to those addressing consumer misunderstandings about switching to CFLs

Content: Select TWO advantages of using audio in Passage 1 to present information about CFLs.

A.Choice: It allows listeners to connect with other people as they share real-world experiences with CFLs.

B.Choice: It allows listeners to rely on tone of voice in order to better understand each speaker's point of view about CFLs.

Key.Rationale: The audio format of the podcast allows listeners to rely on the speaker's tone of voice in order to understand point of view. For example, when asked about the level of mercury in CFLs, the podcast guest remains calm and even-toned in his response, suggesting he believes concerns over mercury exposure in CFLs may be exaggerated.

C.Choice: It allows listeners to interpret the conversational nature of the podcast in a way that makes CFLs seem less threatening.

Key.Rationale: Rather than dwell on detailed technical information regarding the safety of CFLs, the audio podcast briefly touches on a number of benefits of CFLs.

D.Choice: It allows listeners to easily distinguish between viewpoints about CFLs by associating each viewpoint with a different speaker.

E.Choice: It allows listeners to be swayed by the emotional and personal appeals each speaker makes about CFLs throughout the podcast.

Content: The podcast guest in Passage 1 makes several claims about CFLs. Which claim is offered without sufficient supporting evidence?

A.Choice: CFLs provide significant energy savings compared to incandescent bulbs.

B.Choice: Using CFLs is better for the environment than using incandescent bulbs.

C.Choice: The small amount of mercury in CFLs presents little risk to consumers.

Key.Rationale: While the podcast guest does explain to listeners how little mercury is used in CFLs, he does not provide any information about acceptable exposure amounts or any supporting evidence to explain why people should not be concerned about exposure to small amounts of mercury. He also fails to elaborate on whether CFLs even emit mercury or how unlikely it is for people to be exposed to the mercury (which would only happen if the glass tubing broke).

D.Choice: CFLs are easy to dispose of when they eventually burn out.

Content: Select choices to match the claims made by the speaker in Passage 1 with the supporting evidence provided for each claim.

A:CFLs use 75% less energy than traditio.Choice: 1:C͟l͟a͟i͟m: CFLs benefit both the environment and the economy.

Key.Rationale: This detail supports the ideas that CFLs use less energy to function and that people would not have to buy light bulbs as often as traditional bulbs. This supports the claim that CFLs benefit both the environment and the economy.

B:The amount of mercury in a CFL is equi.Choice: 2:C͟l͟a͟i͟m: The environmental disadvantages of CFls can be overcome.

Key.Rationale: This detail gives an example of how little mercury exists within CFLs, which supports the claim that their impact on the environment is not as negative as it is perceived to be.

C:The energy savings from CFLs could pow.Choice: 1:C͟l͟a͟i͟m: CFLs benefit both the environment and the economy.

Key.Rationale: This detail describes how much energy would be saved by using CFLs and how they would not need replacement for a long time, which would benefit the environment and the economy.

Content: Choose the appropriate sentence to be used in the passage to replace the underlined part of the third paragraph.

A.Choice: She the full title and powers of a pharoah assumed.

B.Choice: She assumed the full title and powers of a pharoah.

Key.Rationale: This corrects the inappropriate shift from active to passive voice.
